You are provided with two chemical formulas. Your task is to determine whether the first formula can be obtained from the second by a sequence of legal operations, which include:
'F' means "flip the entire chemical formula around its horizontal axis". For example, F(H2O) = O2H;
'swap(X,Y)' means "swap atoms X and Y in the entire chemical formula". For example, swap(H,O) in H2O results in OH2. Note that 'swap()' may only be called once for each unique pair of atoms (i.e. you cannot swap the same pair of atoms more than once).
